# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: streaming-hls-dash
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Adaptive bitrate streaming works by detecting a user's bandwidth, CPU capability, as well as device type (such as smartphone, desktop computer, or smart TV) in real time, adjusting the quality of the media stream accordingly.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] It requires the use of an encoder which encodes a single source media (video or audio) at multiple bit rates.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The player client switches between streaming the different encodings depending on available resources.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] This results in providing very little buffering, faster start times and a good experience for both high-end and low-end connections.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] More specifically, adaptive bitrate streaming is a method of video streaming over HTTP where the source content is encoded at multiple bit rates.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Each of the different bit rate streams are segmented into small multi-second parts.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] First, the client downloads a manifest file that describes the available stream segments and their respective bit rates.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] During stream start-up, the client usually requests the segments from the lowest bit rate stream.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] If the client finds that the network throughput is greater than the bit rate of the downloaded segment, then it will request a higher bit rate segment.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Later, if the client finds that the network throughput has deteriorated, it will request a lower bit rate segment.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] An adaptive bitrate (ABR) algorithm in the client performs the key function of deciding which bit rate segments to download, based on the current state of the network.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Video streaming services that need to distribute content live or on-demand over the public Internet (also known as over-the-top media services) use adaptive bitrate technology in order to provide consumers with highest quality experience while minimizing buffering interruptions.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] When distributed over HTTP using content delivery networks adaptive bitrate streaming can easily be scaled to support streaming video content to millions of viewers concurrently.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The world's largest streaming services, such as those operated by Netflix, Disney, NBC Universal, Warner Bros.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Discovery, Apple, Google, Amazon and others, have all been actively using adaptive bit rate technology for many years now, making it standard practice for high-end streaming providers.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Traditional server-driven adaptive bitrate streaming provides consumers of streaming media with the best-possible experience, since the media server automatically adapts to any changes in each user's network and playback conditions.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The media and entertainment industry also benefit from adaptive bitrate streaming.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] As the video space grows, content delivery networks and video providers can provide customers with a superior viewing experience.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Adaptive bitrate technology requires additional encoding, but simplifies the overall workflow and creates better results.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] HTTP-based adaptive bitrate streaming technologies yield additional benefits over traditional server-driven adaptive bitrate streaming.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] First, since the streaming technology is built on top of HTTP, contrary to RTP-based adaptive streaming, the packets have no difficulties traversing firewalls and NAT devices.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Second, since HTTP streaming is purely client-driven, all adaptation logic resides at the client.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] This reduces the requirement of persistent connections between server and client application.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Furthermore, the server is not required to maintain session state information on each client, increasing scalability.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Finally, existing HTTP delivery infrastructure, such as HTTP caches and servers, can be seamlessly adopted.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] A scalable CDN is used to deliver media streaming to an Internet audience.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The CDN receives the stream from the source at its Origin server, then replicates it to many or all of its Edge cache servers.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The end-user requests the stream and is redirected to the "closest" Edge server.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] This can be tested using libdash and the Distributed DASH (D-DASH) dataset, which has several mirrors across Europe, Asia and the US.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The use of HTTP-based adaptive streaming allows the Edge server to run a simple HTTP server software, whose license cost is cheap or free, reducing software licensing cost, compared to costly media server licences (e.g., Adobe Flash Media Streaming Server).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The CDN cost for HTTP streaming media is then similar to HTTP web caching CDN cost.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] DVD Forum created a WG1 Special Streaming group in October 2002 that was co-chaired by Toshiba and Phoenix Technologies, with participation from Microsoft, Apple Computer, DTS Inc., Warner Brothers, 20th Century Fox, Digital Deluxe, Disney, Macromedia and Akamai.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The group was responsible for developing and standardizing methods of DVD content online delivery, known as DVDoverIP, that would form an integral part of the Enhanced DVD Format specification (DVD-ENAV).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] One of the specified DVD-ENAV streaming methods described packing MPEG-1 and MPEG-2 DVD TS Sectors into small 2 KB files which could be served to the player using an HTTP server.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The MPEG-1 segments represented a lower bandwidth stream, while the MPEG-2 segments represented a higher bit rate stream.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] An accompanying XML schema provided a simple playlist of bit rates, languages and URL servers.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] However, the specification did not suggest or define dynamic bitrate switching.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] An early HTTP web server based streaming system called SProxy was developed and deployed in the Hewlett-Packard Laboratories in 2006.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] It showed how to use HTTP range requests to break the content into small segments.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] SProxy demonstrated the effectiveness of segment-based streaming, gaining the best Internet penetration due to the wide deployment of firewalls, and reducing the unnecessary traffic transmission if a user chooses to terminate the streaming session earlier before reaching the end.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Modern adaptive bitrate streaming over HTTP was developed by Move Networks between 2004 and 2006, and started gaining worldwide attention in 2007 when it was chosen by ABC Networks as the streaming solution for their new HD video streaming website.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] In October 2010, Move Networks was awarded a patent for its adaptive bitrate streaming invention (US patent no.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] 7818444), based on a provisional patent application filed in April 2004.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Dynamic Adaptive Streaming over HTTP (DASH), also known as MPEG-DASH, is the only adaptive bit-rate HTTP-based streaming solution that is an international standard MPEG-DASH technology was developed under MPEG.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Work on DASH started in 2010 and became a Draft International Standard in January 2011 and an International Standard in November 2011.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The MPEG-DASH standard was published as ISO/IEC 23009-1:2012 in April, 2012.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] MPEG-DASH is a technology related to Adobe Systems HTTP Dynamic Streaming, Apple Inc.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] HTTP Live Streaming (HLS) and Microsoft Smooth Streaming.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] DASH is based on Adaptive HTTP streaming (AHS) in 3GPP Release 9 and on HTTP Adaptive Streaming (HAS) in Open IPTV Forum Release 2.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] As part of their collaboration with MPEG, 3GPP Release 10 has adopted DASH (with specific codecs and operating modes) for use over wireless networks.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The goal of standardizing an adaptive streaming solution is to assure the market that the solution can work universally, unlike other solutions that are more specific to certain vendors, such as Apple's HLS, Microsoft's Smooth Streaming, or Adobe's HDS.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] HTTP Live Streaming (HLS) is an HTTP-based media streaming communications protocol implemented by Apple Inc. as part of QuickTime X and iOS.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] HLS supports both live and video on demand content.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] It works by breaking down media streams or files into short pieces (media segments), which are stored as MPEG-TS or fragmented MP4 files.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] This is typically done at multiple bitrates using a stream or file segmenter application, also known as a packager.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] One such segmenter implementation is provided by Apple.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Additional packagers are available, including free and open source offerings like Google's Shaka Packager and various commercial tools as well - such as Unified Streaming.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The segmenter is also responsible for producing a set of playlist files in the M3U8 format which describe the media chunks.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Each playlist is specific to a given bitrate and contains the relative or absolute URLs to the chunks for that bitrate.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The client is then responsible for requesting the appropriate playlist depending on available bandwidth.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] HTTP Live Streaming is a standard feature in the iPhone 3.0 and newer versions.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Apple has submitted its solution to the IETF for consideration as an Informational Request for Comments.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] This was officially accepted as RFC 8216.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] A number of proprietary and open source solutions exist for both the server implementation (segmenter) and the client player.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] HLS streams can be identified by the playlist URL format extension of m3u8 or MIME type of application/vnd.apple.mpegurl.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] These adaptive streams can be made available in many different bitrates and the client device interacts with the server to obtain the best available bitrate which can reliably be delivered.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Playback of HLS is supported on many platforms, including Safari and native apps on macOS / iOS, Microsoft Edge on Windows 10, ExoPlayer on Android, and the Roku platform.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Many Smart TVs also have native support for HLS.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Playing HLS on other platforms like Chrome / Firefox is typically achieved via a browser / JavaScript player implementation.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Many open source and commercial players are available, including hls.js, video.js http-streaming, BitMovin, JWPlayer, THEOplayer, etc.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] "HTTP Dynamic streaming is the process of efficiently delivering streaming video to users by dynamically switching among different streams of varying quality and size during playback.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] This provides users with the best possible viewing experience their bandwidth and local computer hardware (CPU) can support.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Flash Player and Flash Media Server supported adaptive bit-rate streaming over the traditional RTMP protocol, as well as HTTP, similar to the HTTP-based solutions from Apple and Microsoft, HTTP dynamic streaming being supported in Flash Player 10.1 and later.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] HTTP-based streaming has the advantage of not requiring any firewall ports to be opened outside of the normal ports used by web browsers.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] HTTP-based streaming also allows video fragments to be cached by browsers, proxies, and CDNs, drastically reducing the load on the source server.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Smooth Streaming was developed as an IIS Media Services extension that enabled adaptive streaming of media to clients over HTTP.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The media storage format was based on the ISO base media file format and published by Microsoft as the Protected Interoperable File Format specification.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Microsoft was actively involved with 3GPP, MPEG and DECE organizations' efforts to standardize adaptive bit-rate HTTP streaming, which ultimately resulted in the publication of the DASH standard.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Microsoft provided Smooth Streaming Client software development kits for Silverlight and Windows Phone 7, as well as a Smooth Streaming Porting Kit that could be used for other client operating systems, such as Apple iOS, Android, and Linux.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] IIS Media Services 4.0, released in November 2010, introduced a feature which enabled Live Smooth Streaming H.264/AAC videos to be dynamically repackaged into the Apple HTTP Adaptive Streaming format and delivered to iOS devices without the need for re-encoding.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Between 2009 and 2013, Microsoft successfully demonstrated delivery of both live and on-demand 1080p HD video with Smooth Streaming to Silverlight clients.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] In 2010, Microsoft also partnered with NVIDIA to demonstrate live streaming of 1080p stereoscopic 3D video to PCs equipped with NVIDIA 3D Vision technology.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] In 2013 Microsoft shifted its media services product offering to the cloud where it continued to support Smooth Streaming as a core component of Azure Media Services.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] However, development and adoption of MPEG DASH and HLS as industry standards gradually displaced Smooth Streaming as Microsoft's preferred adaptive streaming technology by the end of that decade.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] In June 2023 Microsoft announced the retirement of Azure Media Services, effective June 2024, and while the announcement didn't explicitly mention Smooth Streaming by name it effectively meant the end of support for Smooth Streaming in any active Microsoft products.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] CMAF is a presentation container format used for the delivery of both HLS and MPEG-DASH.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Hence, it is intended to simplify delivery of HTTP-based streaming media.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] It was proposed in 2016 by Apple and Microsoft and officially published in 2018.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] In recent years, the benefits of self-learning algorithms in adaptive bitrate streaming have been investigated in academia.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] While most of the initial self-learning approaches are implemented at the server-side (e.g., performing admission control using reinforcement learning or artificial neural networks), more recent research is focusing on the development of self-learning HTTP Adaptive Streaming clients.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Multiple approaches have been presented in literature using the SARSA or Q-learning algorithm.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] In all of these approaches, the client state is modeled using, among others, information about the current perceived network throughput and buffer filling level.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Based on this information, the self-learning client autonomously decides which quality level to select for the next video segment.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] The learning process is steered using feedback information, representing the Quality of Experience (QoE) (e.g., based on the quality level, the number of switches and the number of video freezes).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Furthermore, it was shown that multi-agent Q-learning can be applied to improve QoE fairness among multiple adaptive streaming clients.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] HTTP-based adaptive bit rate technologies are significantly more operationally complex than traditional streaming technologies.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] Some of the documented considerations are things such as additional storage and encoding costs, and challenges with maintaining quality globally.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] There have also been some interesting dynamics found around the interactions between complex adaptive bit rate logic competing with complex TCP flow control logic.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] With no single clearly defined or open standard for the digital rights management used in the above methods, there is no 100% compatible way of delivering restricted or time-sensitive content to any device or player.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/adaptive-bitrate-streaming] This also proves to be a problem with digital rights management being employed by any streaming protocol.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Similar to Apple's HTTP Live Streaming (HLS) solution, MPEG-DASH works by breaking the content into a sequence of small segments, which are served over HTTP.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Each segment contains a short interval of playback time of content that is potentially many hours in duration, such as a movie or the live broadcast of a sport event.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] The content is made available at a variety of different bit rates, i.e., alternative segments encoded at different bit rates covering aligned short intervals of playback time.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] While the content is being played back by an MPEG-DASH client, the client uses a bit rate adaptation (ABR) algorithm to automatically select the segment with the highest bit rate possible that can be downloaded in time for playback without causing stalls or re-buffering events in the playback.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Thus, an MPEG-DASH client can seamlessly adapt to changing network conditions and provide high quality playback with few stalls or re-buffering events.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH is the first adaptive bit-rate HTTP-based streaming solution that is an international standard.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH should not be confused with a transport protocol — the transport protocol that MPEG-DASH uses depends on which version of HTTP is used: TCP is the transport over which HTTP and HTTP/2 run, while HTTP/3 runs over QUIC (which in turn runs over UDP).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH uses existing HTTP web server infrastructure that is used for delivery of essentially all World Wide Web content.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] It allows devices like Internet-connected televisions, TV set-top boxes, desktop computers, smartphones, tablets, etc. to receive multimedia content (video, TV, radio, etc.) delivered via the Internet, coping with variable Internet receiving conditions.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Standardizing an adaptive streaming solution is meant to provide confidence to the market that the solution can be adopted for universal deployment, compared to similar but more proprietary solutions like Smooth Streaming by Microsoft, or HDS by Adobe.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Unlike HDS, or Smooth Streaming, DASH is codec-agnostic, which means it can use content encoded with any coding format, such as H.265, H.264, VP9, etc.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH technology was developed under MPEG.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Work on DASH started in 2010; it became a Draft International Standard in January 2011, and an International Standard in November 2011.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] The MPEG-DASH standard was published in April, 2012 but has been revised in 2019 and then once more in 2022 as [1].
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] DASH is a technology related to Adobe Systems HTTP Dynamic Streaming, Apple Inc.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] The DASH Industry Forum (DASH-IF) further promotes and catalyzes the adoption of MPEG-DASH and helps transition it from a specification into a real business.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] It consists of major streaming and media companies, including Microsoft, Netflix, Google, Ericsson, Samsung, Adobe, etc. and creates guidelines on the usage of DASH for different use cases in practice.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH is integrated in other standards, e.g.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH is supported in HbbTV (as of Version 1.5).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] DASH is an adaptive bitrate streaming technology where a multimedia file is partitioned into one or more segments and delivered to a client using HTTP.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] A media presentation description (MPD) describes segment information (timing, URL, media characteristics like video resolution and bit rates), and can be organized in different ways such as SegmentList, SegmentTemplate, SegmentBase and SegmentTimeline, depending on the use case.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Segments can contain any media data, however the specification provides specific guidance and formats for use with two types of containers: ISO base media file format (e.g.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MP4 file format) or MPEG-2 Transport Stream.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] An early predecessor of DASH was an HTTP web server based streaming system called SProxy, developed and deployed in the Hewlett Packard Laboratories in 2006.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] DASH standard does not specify the adaptive bitrate streaming (ABR) logic.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] The current MPEG-DASH reference client dash.js offers both buffer-based (BOLA) and hybrid (DYNAMIC) bit rate adaptation algorithms.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] DASH is also agnostic to the underlying application layer protocol.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Thus, DASH can be used with other application protocols besides HTTP, e.g., DASH over CCN.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] On July 27, 2015, MPEG LA announced a call for MPEG-DASH-related patents in order to create a single patent pool for this technology.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG LA announced its MPEG-DASH patent portfolio licence.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-LA claims that the included patents are essential to the MPEG Dynamic Adaptive Streaming over HTTP standard.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH is available natively on Android through the ExoPlayer, on Samsung Smart TVs 2012+, LG Smart TV 2012+, Sony TV 2012+, Philips NetTV 4.1+, Panasonic Viera 2013+ and Chromecast.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] YouTube as well as Netflix already support MPEG-DASH, and different MPEG-DASH players are available.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] While MPEG-DASH isn't directly supported in HTML5, there are JavaScript implementations of MPEG-DASH which allow using MPEG-DASH in web browsers using the HTML5 Media Source Extensions (MSE).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] There are also JavaScript implementations such as the bitdash player which support DRM for MPEG-DASH using the HTML5 Encrypted Media Extensions.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] In combination with WebGL, the HTML5-based adaptive bitrate streaming of MPEG-DASH enables also the efficient streaming of 360° video for live and on-demand use cases.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Note that no specific support is required from the server for DASH content, with the exception of Live Streaming.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Windows 10 used to have native support for DASH streaming in EdgeHTML, a proprietary browser engine that was used in Microsoft Edge (now referred to as Edge Legacy) before the transition to the Chromium-based Blink browser engine.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Edge Legacy was included in Windows 10 up till version 2004.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] It was replaced by Edge Chromium in version 20H2.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] DASH support on other browsers & operating systems is available via Media Source Extensions.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/guides-streaming] In this guide, we'll examine the techniques used to stream audio and/or video media on the web, and how you can optimize your code, your media, your server, and the options you use while performing the streaming to bring out the best quality and performance possible.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/guides-streaming] In addition to the configuration of the server and the streaming code, there are sometimes special protocols which can be used to optimize performance.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/guides-streaming] For example, because many websites' mobile-specific content assume that mobile browsers support HLS, Firefox for Android does as well, in order to avoid strange compatibility errors from occurring due to this assumption being incorrect.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/guides-streaming] The desktop version of Firefox, however, does not support HLS.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/guides-streaming] HLS uses playlists to allow the user to not only select the media to stream, but also to choose among versions or forms of the same media.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/guides-streaming] For example, HLS lets the server stream a video with multiple audio streams which the user can choose from, in order to hear their own language.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/guides-streaming] Additionally, forms of the stream can be provided which are optimized for different network conditions.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/guides-streaming] In this way, live streams can be made flexible and highly performant.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/guides-streaming] As of mid-2017, HLS has been standardized as RFC 8216.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] HLS resembles MPEG-DASH in that it works by breaking the overall stream into a sequence of small HTTP-based file downloads, each downloading one short chunk of an overall potentially unbounded transport stream.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] A list of available streams, encoded at different bit rates, is sent to the client using an extended M3U playlist.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Based on standard HTTP transactions, HTTP Live Streaming can traverse any firewall or proxy server that lets through standard HTTP traffic, unlike UDP-based protocols such as RTP.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] This also allows content to be offered from conventional HTTP servers and delivered over widely available HTTP-based content delivery networks.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The standard also includes a standard encryption mechanism and secure-key distribution using HTTPS, which together provide a simple DRM system.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Later versions of the protocol also provide for trick-mode fast-forward and rewind and for integration of subtitles.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Apple has documented HTTP Live Streaming as an Internet Draft (Individual Submission), the first stage in the process of publishing it as a Request for Comments (RFC).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] As of December 2015, the authors of that document have requested the RFC Independent Stream Editor (ISE) to publish the document as an informational (non-standard) RFC outside of the IETF consensus process.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] In August 2017, RFC 8216 was published to describe version 7 of the protocol.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] HTTP Live Streaming uses a conventional web server, that implements support for HTTP Live Streaming (HLS), to distribute audiovisual content and requires specific software, such as OBS to fit the content into a proper format (codec) for transmission in real time over a network.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Codify and encapsulate the input video flow in a proper format for the delivery.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Then it is prepared for distribution by segmenting it into different files.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] In the process of intake, the video is encoded and segmented to generate video fragments and index file.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Request and download all the files and resources, assembling them so that they can be presented to the user as a continuous flow video.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] and then the several media files available.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The playback software assembles the sequence to allow continued display to the user.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] HTTP Live Streaming provides mechanisms for players to adapt to unreliable network conditions without causing user-visible playback stalling.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] For example, on an unreliable wireless network, HLS allows the player to use a lower quality video, thus reducing bandwidth usage.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] HLS videos can be made highly available by providing multiple servers for the same video, allowing the player to swap seamlessly if one of the servers fails.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] To enable a player to adapt to the bandwidth of the network, the original video is encoded in several distinct quality levels.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The server serves an index, called a *master playlist*, of these encodings, called *variant streams*.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The player can then choose between the variant streams during playback, changing back and forth seamlessly as network conditions change.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] At WWDC 2016 Apple announced the inclusion of byte-range addressing for fragmented MP4 files, or fMP4, allowing content to be played via HLS without the need to multiplex it into MPEG-2 Transport Stream.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The industry considered this as a step towards compatibility between HLS and MPEG-DASH.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The remainder of this section describes Apple's ALHLS.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] It reduces the glass-to-glass delay when streaming via HLS by reducing the time to start live stream playbacks and maintain that time during a live-streaming event.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] It works by adding partial media segment files into the mix, much like MPEG-CMAF's fMP4.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Unlike CMAF, ALHLS also supports partial MPEG-2 TS transport files.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] A partial media segment is a standard segment (e.g.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] 6 seconds) split into equal segments of less than a second (e.g.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The standard first segment is replaced by the series of partial segments.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Subsequent segments are of the standard size.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] HTTP/2 is required to push the segments along with the playlist, reducing the overhead of establishing repeated HTTP/TCP connections.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Apple also added new tools: *tsrecompressor* produces and encodes a continuous low latency stream of audio and video.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The *mediastreamsegmenter* tool is now available in a low-latency version.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] It is an HLS segmenter that takes in a UDP/MPEG-TS stream from tsrecompressor and generates a media playlist, including the new tags above.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Support for low-latency HLS is available in tvOS 13 beta, and iOS & iPadOS 14.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] On April 30, 2020, Apple added the low latency specifications to the second edition of the main HLS specification.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Dynamic ad insertion is supported in HLS using splice information based on SCTE-35 specification.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The SCTE-35 splice message is inserted into the media playlist file using the EXT-X-DATERANGE tag.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Each SCTE-35 splice_info_section() is represented by an EXT-X-DATERANGE tag with a SCTE35-CMD attribute.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] A SCTE-35 splice out/in pair signaled by the splice_insert() commands is represented by one or more EXT-X-DATERANGE tags carrying the same ID attribute.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The SCTE-35 splice out command should have the SCTE35-OUT attribute and the splice in command should have the SCTE35-IN attribute.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Between the two EXT-X-DATERANGE tags that contain the SCTE35-OUT and SCTE35-IN attributes respectively, there may be a sequence of media segment URIs.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] These media segments normally represent ad programs that can be replaced by the local or customized ad.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The ad replacement does not require the replacement of the media files, only the URIs in the playlist need to be changed to point to different ad programs.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] The ad replacement can be done on the origin server or on the client's media-playing device.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Windows 10 used to have native support for HTTP Live Streaming in EdgeHTML, a proprietary browser engine that was used in Microsoft Edge (now referred to as Edge Legacy) before the transition to the Chromium-based Blink browser engine.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/http-live-streaming] Along with Windows 11, Microsoft released an updated Media Player that supports HLS natively.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] Although originally designed for audio files, such as MP3, it is commonly used to point media players to audio and video sources, including online sources.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] M3U was originally developed by Fraunhofer for use with their WinPlay3 software, but numerous media players and software applications now support the format.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] Careless handling of M3U playlists has been the cause of vulnerabilities in many music players such as VLC media player, iTunes, Winamp, and many others.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] There is no formal specification for the M3U format; it is a *de facto* standard.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] An M3U file is a plain text file that specifies the locations of one or more media files.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] The file is saved with the `m3u` filename extension if the text is encoded in the local system's default non-Unicode encoding (e.g., a Windows codepage), or with the `m3u8` extension if the text is UTF-8 encoded.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] The `mp3url` extension was originally supported by Winplay3, but fell out of use.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] Each entry ends with a line break which separates it from the following one.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] Furthermore, some devices only accept line breaks represented as `CR LF`, but do not recognize a single `LF`.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] The M3U file can also include comments, prefaced by the `#` character.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] In **extended M3U**, `#` also introduces extended M3U directives which are terminated by a colon `:` if they support parameters.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] The use of UTF-8 encoding is mandatory in M3U playlists with the **M3U8** file extension.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] The system codepage is usually assumed for `.m3u` but this is often UTF-8 as well nowadays so the distinction has mostly been lost in practice.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] Apple used the extended M3U format, UTF-8 encoded, as a base for their HTTP Live Streaming (HLS) which was documented in an Independent Submission Stream RFC in 2017 as RFC 8216.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] Therein, a *master playlist* references segment playlists which usually contain URLs for short parts of the media stream.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] Some tags only apply to the former type and some only to the latter type of playlist, but they all begin with `#EXT-X-`.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] With television broadcasting via the internet protocol (IPTV), M3U playlists are frequently used to store the (start) URLs of the streams, so each entry represents a channel.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] As usual for continuous streams, the length info directly after `#EXTINF:` is set to `-1`.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] Unlike HLS, other structured information is not provided in separate info lines but with a key–value syntax before the mandatory comma following the length.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] The only Internet media type registered for M3U and M3U8 is `application/vnd.apple.mpegurl`, registered in 2009 and only referring to the playlist format as used in HLS applications.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] The current proposal for the HLS playlist format acknowledges two media types which it treats as equivalent: `application/vnd.apple.mpegurl` and `audio/mpegurl`.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] Likewise, these are the two types recommended for HLS use by Microsoft.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] These types, plus `application/vnd.apple.mpegurl` and `application/vnd.apple.mpegurl.audio`, are supported for HLS applications by (for example) Microsoft's Windows 10 and Internet Explorer 9, and LG's WebOS.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] The following tag editor software allows users to edit the ID3 tags in MP3 files, and has support for creating M3U files.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/m3u] The following media player software supports playing M3U files.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] RTMPS, which is RTMP over a Transport Layer Security (TLS/SSL) connection.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] RTMPE, which is RTMP encrypted using Adobe's own security mechanism.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] While the details of the implementation are proprietary, the mechanism uses industry standard cryptographic primitives.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] RTMPT, which is encapsulated within HTTP requests to traverse firewalls.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] RTMPT is frequently found utilizing cleartext requests on TCP ports 80 and 443 to bypass most corporate traffic filtering.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The encapsulated session may carry plain RTMP, RTMPS, or RTMPE packets within.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] RTMFP, which is RTMP over User Datagram Protocol (UDP) instead of TCP, replacing RTMP Chunk Stream.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The Secure Real-Time Media Flow Protocol suite has been developed by Adobe Systems and enables end‐users to connect and communicate directly with each other (P2P).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] E-RTMP, or Enhanced RTMP, is an enhancement to the RTMP and FLV specifications designed to improve streaming capabilities while maintaining compatibility with existing RTMP infrastructure.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] E-RTMP enhances RTMP by adding features such as advanced timestamp precision, multitrack capabilities, expanded codec support, FourCC signaling, and a reconnect request feature.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] While the primary motivation for RTMP was to be a protocol for playing Flash Video, it is also used in some other applications, such as the Adobe LiveCycle Data Services ES.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] RTMP is a TCP-based protocol which maintains persistent connections and allows low-latency communication.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] To deliver streams smoothly and transmit as much information as possible, it splits streams into fragments, and their size is negotiated dynamically between the client and server.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Sometimes, it is kept unchanged; the default fragment sizes are 64 bytes for audio data, and 128 bytes for video data and most other data types.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Fragments from different streams may then be interleaved, and multiplexed over a single connection.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] With longer data chunks, the protocol thus carries only a one-byte header per fragment, so incurring very little overhead.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] However, in practice, individual fragments are not typically interleaved.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Instead, the interleaving and multiplexing is done at the packet level, with RTMP packets across several different active channels being interleaved in such a way as to ensure that each channel meets its bandwidth, latency, and other quality-of-service requirements.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Packets interleaved in this fashion are treated as indivisible, and are not interleaved on the fragment level.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The RTMP defines several virtual channels on which packets may be sent and received, and which operate independently of each other.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] For example, there is a channel for handling RPC requests and responses, a channel for video stream data, a channel for audio stream data, a channel for out-of-band control messages (fragment size negotiation, etc.), and so on.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] During a typical RTMP session, several channels may be active simultaneously at any given time.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] When RTMP data is encoded, a packet header is generated.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The packet header specifies, amongst other matters, the ID of the channel on which it is to be sent, a timestamp of when it was generated (if necessary), and the size of the packet's payload.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] This header is then followed by the actual payload content of the packet, which is fragmented according to the currently agreed-upon fragment size before it is sent over the connection.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The packet header itself is never fragmented, and its size does not count towards the data in the packet's first fragment.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] In other words, only the actual packet payload (the media data) is subject to fragmentation.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] At a higher level, the RTMP encapsulates MP3 or AAC audio and FLV1 video multimedia streams, and can make remote procedure calls (RPCs) using the Action Message Format.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Any RPC services required are made asynchronously, using a single client/server request/response model, such that real-time communication is not required.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] In RTMP Tunneled (RTMPT), RTMP data is encapsulated and exchanged via HTTP, and messages from the client (the media player, in this case) are addressed to port 80 (the default for HTTP) on the server.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The protocol works by sending commands through the POST URL, and AMF messages through the POST body.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Adobe has released a specification for version 1.0 of the protocol, dated 21 December 2012.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The web landing page leading to that specification notes that "To benefit customers who want to protect their content, the open RTMP specification does not include Adobe's unique secure RTMP measures".
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Stefan Richter, author of some books on Flash, noted in 2008 that while Adobe is vague as to which patents apply to RTMP, U.S. patent 7,246,356 appears to be one of them.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] In 2011, Adobe did sue Wowza Media Systems claiming, among other things, infringement of their RTMP patents.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] In 2015, Adobe and Wowza announced that the lawsuits have been settled and dismissed with prejudice.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Packets are sent over a TCP connection, which is established first between client and server.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] They contain a header and a body which, in the case of connection and control commands, is encoded using the Action Message Format (AMF).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The header is split into the *Basic Header* (shown as detached from the rest, in the diagram) and *Chunk Message Header*.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The Basic Header is the only constant part of the packet and is usually composed of a single *composite* byte, where the two most significant bits are the Chunk Type (*fmt* in the specification) and the rest form the Stream ID.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The Chunk Message Header contains meta-data information such as the message size (measured in bytes), the *Timestamp Delta* and *Message Type*.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] This last value is a single byte and defines whether the packet is an audio, video, command or "low level" RTMP packet such as an RTMP Ping.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The packet starts with a *Basic Header* of a single byte (0x03) where the two most significant bits (b**00**000011) define a chunk header type of 0 while the rest (b00**000011**) define a Chunk Stream ID of 3.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The six least significant bits that form the Stream ID can take values between 3 and 63.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Some values have special meaning, like 1 that stands for an extended ID format, in which case there will be two bytes following that.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] A value of two is for low level messages such as Ping and Set Client Bandwidth.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The Message Type ID byte defines whether the packet contains audio/video data, a remote object or a command.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Following the header, 0x02 denotes a string of size 0x000C and values 0x63 0x72 ...
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Following that we have a 0x00 (number) which is the transaction id of value 2.0.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The last byte is 0x05 (null) which means there are no arguments.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Some of the message types shown above, such as Ping and Set Client/Server Bandwidth, are considered low level RTMP protocol messages which do not use the AMF encoding format.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The transaction id is used for commands that can have a reply.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The value can be either a string like in the example above or one or more objects, each composed of a set of key/value pairs where the keys are always encoded as strings while the values can be any AMF data type, including complex types like arrays.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] They start with a stream Id of 0x02 which implies a full (type 0) header and have a message type of 0x04.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The first two bytes of the message body define the Ping Type, which can apparently take six possible values.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] This relates to messages that have to do with the client up-stream and server down-stream bit-rate.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The body is composed of four bytes showing the bandwidth value, with a possible extension of one byte which sets the Limit Type.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] This can have one of three possible values which can be: hard, soft or dynamic (either soft or hard).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The value received in the four bytes of the body.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] A default value of 128 bytes exists, and the message is sent only when a change is wanted.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] After establishing a TCP connection, an RTMP connection is established first, performing a handshake through the exchange of three packets from each side (also referred to as Chunks in the official documentation).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] These are referred in the official spec as C0-2 for the client sent packets and S0-2 for the server side respectively and are not to be confused with RTMP packets that can be exchanged only after the handshake is complete.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] These packets have a structure of their own and C1 contains a field setting the "epoch" timestamp, but since this can be set to zero, as is done in third party implementations, the packet can be simplified.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The client initialises the connection by sending the C0 packet with a constant value of 0x03 representing the current protocol version.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] It follows straight with C1 without waiting for S0 to be received first which contains 1536 bytes, with the first four representing the epoch timestamp, the second four all being 0, and the rest being random (and which can be set to 0 in third party implementations).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] C2 and S2 are an echo of S1 and C1 respectively, except with the second four bytes being the time the respective message was received (instead of 0).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] After C2 and S2 are received, the handshake is considered complete.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] At this point, the client, and server can negotiate a connection by exchanging AMF encoded messages.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] These include key value pairs which relate to variables that are needed for a connection to be established.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The Flash Media Server and other implementations uses the concept of an "app" to conceptually define a container for audio/video and other content, implemented as a folder on the server root which contains the media files to be streamed.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The first variable contains the name of this app as "sample" which is the name provided by the Wowza Server for their testing.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The `flashVer` string is the same as returned by the Action-script `getversion()` function.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The `audioCodec` and `videoCodec` are encoded as doubles and their meaning can be found in the original spec.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The same is true for the `videoFunction` variable, which in this case is the self-explanatory SUPPORT_VID_CLIENT_SEEK constant.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Of special interest is the `objectEncoding` which will define whether the rest of the communication will make use of the extended AMF3 format or not.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] As version 3 is the current default, the flash client has to be told explicitly in Action-script code to use AMF0 if that is requested.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The server then replies with a ServerBW, a ClientBW and a SetPacketSize message sequence, finally followed by an Invoke, with an example message.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Some values above are serialised into properties of a generic Action-script Object, which is then passed to the NetConnection event listener.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The `clientId` will establish a number for the session to be started by the connection.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Object encoding must match the value previously set.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] To start a video stream, the client sends a "createStream" invocation followed by a ping message, followed by a "play" invocation with the file name as argument.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The server will then reply with a series of "onStatus" commands followed by the video data as encapsulated within RTMP messages.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] After a connection is established, media is sent by encapsulating the content of FLV tags into RTMP messages of type 8 and 9 for audio and video, respectively.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] This refers to the HTTP tunneled version of the protocol.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] It communicates over port 80 and passes the AMF data inside HTTP POST request and responses.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The first request has an `/fcs/ident2` path, and the correct reply is a 404 Not Found error.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The client then sends an /open/1 request where the server must reply with a 200 ok appending a random number that will be used as the session identifier for the said communication.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] In this example, 1728724019 is returned in the response body.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] From now on, the `/idle/<session id>/<sequence #>` is a polling request where the session id has been generated and returned from the server and the sequence is just a number that increments by one for every request.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The appropriate response is a 200 OK, with an integer returned in the body signifying the interval time.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The open-source RTMP client command-line tool rtmpdump is designed to play back or save to disk the full RTMP stream, including the RTMPE protocol Adobe uses for encryption.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] RTMPdump runs on Linux, Android, Solaris, Mac OS X, and most other Unix-derived operating systems, as well as Microsoft Windows.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Originally supporting all versions of 32-bit Windows including Windows 98, from version 2.2 the software will run only on Windows XP and above (although earlier versions remain fully functional).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Packages of the rtmpdump suite of software are available in the major open-source repositories (Linux distributions).
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Development of RTMPdump was restarted in October 2009, outside the United States, at the MPlayer site.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The current version features greatly improved functionality, and has been rewritten to take advantage of the benefits of the C programming language.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] In particular, the main functionality was built into a library (librtmp) which can easily be used by other applications.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The RTMPdump developers have also written support for librtmp for MPlayer, FFmpeg, XBMC, cURL, VLC and a number of other open source software projects.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Use of librtmp provides these projects with full support of RTMP in all its variants without any additional development effort.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] FLVstreamer is a fork of RTMPdump, without the code, which Adobe claims violates the DMCA in the USA.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] This was developed as a response to Adobe's attempt in 2008 to suppress RTMPdump.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] FLVstreamer is an RTMP client that will save a stream of audio or video content from any RTMP server to disk, if encryption (RTMPE) is not enabled on the stream.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] The above variants are additions made on top of RTMP.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] However, the limited codec selections of FLV and RTMP has necessitated the industry to add things to the format and the protocol directly.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] RTMP interally uses its own four-bit "codec ID" instead of standard FourCC to identify the set of codecs it supports.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Audio and video codec IDs are considered to be in different namespaces, so using the same value does not cause any conflict: for example, in Adobe's baseline standard, audio codec 7 is G.711A and video codec 7 is H.264.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] In China, Kingsoft Cloud assigned H.265 to video codec "12" in 2018, a practice soon accepted by other industry players such as Bilibili.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] In 2020, Xia Chu of ZLMediaKit assigned Opus to audio codec 13.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] All *ad hoc* additions to the coded ID field have been made obsolete by E-RTMP.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] E-RTMP does not reuse the IDs 12 and 13, making it compatible with the Chinese *ad hoc* extensions.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Enhanced RTMP (E-RTMP) is an enhancement to the Real-Time Messaging Protocol (RTMP) and FLV specifications, modernizing streaming workflows while maintaining compatibility with existing RTMP infrastructure.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Developed as an open specification, E-RTMP was published by the Veovera Software Organization, with contributions from Adobe, Google, Twitch, and others.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] E-RTMP enhances RTMP’s capabilities while ensuring interoperability with existing RTMP implementations.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] For example, a legacy decoder would not know how to decode frames containing reserved ("new") headers, but it would still be able to forward it properly.
[src:streaming-hls-dash/real-time-messaging-protocol] Because many changes in E-RTMP are made to the FLV format layer, E-RTMP also includes an extension to the FLV file format that can be used independently of E-RTMP. ffmpeg calls this format "enhanced FLV".
